<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Superman">Superman</h3>



<p>The Superman is a bodyweight movement that prioritizes engagement of the back muscles and activates the erector spinae, glutes, posterior deltoids, and hamstrings.&nbsp;</p>



<p>It has a <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6165989/#:~:text=In%20previous%20EMG,al.%2C%202010)." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">61%â€“77% maximum voluntary contraction</a> of the lumbar multifidus compared to other back extension exercises. The <a href="https://bmcmusculoskeletdisord.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12891-020-03257-7#:~:text=Lumbar%20multifidus%20(LM)%20is%20regarded%20as%20the%20major%20stabilizing%20muscle%20of%20the%20spine.%20The%20effects%20of%20exercise%20therapy%20in%20low%20back%20pain%20(LBP)%20are%20attributed%20to%20this%20muscle." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">lumbar multifidus</a> functions as an essential lumber spine stabilizer, with low back pain frequently linked to weakness in this muscle. Integrating the Superman in your home workouts can strengthen back muscles while preventing lower back pain.&nbsp;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="Supermans" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980244219?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Superman Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Lay on your stomach on a mat.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Straighten your arms above your head about shoulder-width apart.</li>



<li>Keep your legs straight and feet close together. This is your starting position.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Inhale.</li>



<li>Exhale and simultaneously draw your arms and legs off the ground.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Pause when you create about six inches of space from the floor.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Inhale and return to the starting position.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips&nbsp;</h4>



<ul>
<li>Do not arch the neck up, as this can stress this area. Maintain a neutral spine throughout the exercise.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Prioritize slow and controlled movements to increase muscle activation over fast repetitions.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



