<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Seated-Rear-Delt-Fly">Dumbbell Seated Rear Delt Fly</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/seated-dumbbell-rear-delt-fly" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell seated rear delt fly</a> is an effective isolation exercise for targeting the posterior deltoids. Isolation exercises are single-jointed movements used to focus on one muscle group. It also engages the rhomboids, trapezius, and lateral deltoids. This exercise helps create a defined and balanced appearance by stimulating muscle growth in all aspects of the upper body.&nbsp;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Seated Dumbbell Rear Delt Fly" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/1000648907?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Seated Rear Delt Fly Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>You will need a flat bench and two dumbbells for this exercise.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Sit on the end of the bench with your feet flat on the floor.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Position feet shoulder-width apart.</li>



<li>Hinge the torso forward enough to mimic a bent-over position.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Allow your arms to hang by your thighs behind your knees.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Grip the dumbbells in a neutral grip with palms facing you. This is your starting position.</li>



<li>Inhale.</li>



<li>Exhale and drive your arms out to the sides until they are parallel to the floor.</li>



<li>Inhale and return to the starting position.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Do not use momentum to execute this exercise. Swinging the arms or body creates momentum that detracts from desired muscle engagement. Focus on slow and controlled movements to emphasize muscle engagement.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Maintain a neutral spine and straight back to prevent issues like neck and lower back pain. Do not arch the neck to look up or hunch the shoulders forward.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



